My first book “The Big Reveal” is coming out April 4th! 

I wrote this book to make a case for the radical history of drag…a folk art that has existed for centuries worldwide and continues to advocate for the joy and survival of queer and trans people everywhere. Drag saves lives! In this book I wanted to share how it saved mine…and how it taught me to keep strengthening and pushing forward, no matter the opposition. Please read and share our amazing story!

Available for preorder on houseofvelour.com

Special thanks to @maccosmetics for their sponsorship of NightGowns! Photos by @ajjordanphoto and @sidewalkkilla! #liveatlpr
Thank you @goodmorningamerica ! ⏰💖 My book “The Big Reveal: An Illustrated Manifesto of Drag” comes out Tuesday 4/4!  Wearing @christopherjohnrogers

Preparem o death drop: @sashavelour é a capa de junho da #ELLEView! A drag queen fez história com sua cascata de rosas na final da nona temporada de RuPaul's Drag Race, mas é muito mais do que seu momento famoso. Designer, ilustradora, quadrinista e ativista, ela lota shows por onde passa e acaba de lançar o seu primeiro livro, "The big reveal: an illustrated manifesto of drag".

Sasha foi uma das primeiras drags do programa a questionar os padrões da indústria, como a necessidade de usar peruca ou marcar o corpo com enchimentos –, ainda que o faça quando tem vontade. Para ela, drag é uma forma de arte. E arte precisa ser livre!

Sasha Velour veste @walerioaraujo 

Para ler mais sobre a drag e saber como foi o dia super especial que passamos com @sashavelour durante as fotos que recheiam essa edição, assine a #ELLEView por apenas R$9,99.

Brace yourselves and prepare for the big reveal: @sashavelour is the coverstar of our june #ELLEview! The drag queen made history with a cascade of roses falling from her wig in the season nine finale of RuPaul's Drag Race, but she's so much more than that famous moment. The visual artist, cartoonist, activist and now debut author sells out shows around the world and just released her first, bestselling book, "The Big Reveal: An Illustrated Manifesto of Drag,” available now for purchase.

Sasha has been a major disruptor in drag, shifting industry standards, including the need to wear a wig or to conform to binary standards of gender. To her, drag is an art form. And art needs to be free!

Sasha Velour wears @walerioaraujo 

To read more about the super special day we spent with @sashavelour and to view the pictures in this issue, subscribe to #ELLEView for R$9,99.

A revolutionary little nap!

I did this photoshoot with @mettieostrowski to accompany the “Revolution” chapter from “The Big Reveal”—all about the connections between drag and queer and trans activism. I’ve been obsessed with our activist history recently. Over the last few years amidst new anti-trans and anti-drag laws, I’ve grown to expect every day that someone will ask me to defend drag or my queer identity and  threats of violence, misinformation, loss of income has increased so much. I turn to history to remind me that progress and discrimination are cyclical, but that we have come an enormous way thanks to bold disruptions and acts of protest.

I have felt a little withdrawn from social media out of sheer exhaustion. Kind of fitting that this photo is about someone taking a much-needed (or indulgent?) little rest. I think we all need our moments of pause. But I aspire to hurl more bottles and coins!

 I’ll be touring Europe and the UK with The Big Reveal Live Show from Oct 20 - Nov 22 (check out dates on my site!)

A few years back, I found a box of unfinished quilts made by my maternal great grandmothers nearly 100 years ago in Michigan and Oklahoma. My mom had been saving them to repurpose into her own quilt, but she never found the right pattern for it before she passed away. 

I always remember her quilting—it was the type of art she loved to make, and she was so good at it. She taught me how to sew as her quilting assistant. Of course it had to be perfect, or else she’d do it herself! But I loved her philosophy that it is always better to repurpose something than let it sit in a box.

I asked the incredible Pierretta Viktori @blackandwhitestriped to help me quilt the scraps into a dress for “The Big Reveal.” (I still am not good enough to do it myself!) Today it is one of my most special pieces in drag.

An homage to Barbette—an American drag queen aerialist who was a sensation in Europe in the 20s, enthralling huge crowds of the time including artists like Jean Cocteau and Man Ray. Despite being the toast of society (like many drag artists have been in the past), Barbette faced a hard life—was arrested because of her queerness in London, struggled to find work after an injury in the 30s (although she did serve as the drag coach for “Some Like It Hot”), and died after dealing with chronic pain in their Texas hometown, largely forgotten by the throngs that once adored them. 

That’s drag baby! The full picture, unfortunately—from glamour to tragedy and all the camp you find in between. Today Barbette is an inspiration to so many drag artists, and her name is spoken with deep respect again. To me there is something spiritual in that.

Dracula, but in the style of Maria Callas?

As a kid, I was obsessed with Dracula because dressing up as a  vampire was my excuse to wear flowing robes (in my head they were dresses!) and lipstick. I fell in love with art and theater partly because of the freedom it gave me with my expressions of gender! 

I’ve always been a little drag performer. I don’t believe drag is something that can be taught or forced. Just like being queer, it’s something we just know about ourselves, and all we need is a little permission to choose freely!
